    "summary": "Mari, located on the middle Euphrates near the modern border between Syria and Iraq, was one of the most important cities in the ancient Near East during the third millennium BC. In its early phase, approximately 2900–2550 BC, Mari was a significant urban centre and trading hub strategically positioned to control river commerce between Mesopotamia and the Mediterranean world. The city's position allowed it to profit from traffic in metals, timber, textiles, and other commodities flowing between the resource-rich regions of Anatolia and the Levant and the densely populated cities of southern Mesopotamia.\n\nArchaeological excavations at Mari, conducted primarily by French archaeologists from the 1930s onward, revealed a city with impressive palaces, temples, and extensive storage facilities. The city interacted politically with both Sumerian and Akkadian powers, at times autonomous and at times under external domination. Mari maintained its own distinctive cultural character, blending Mesopotamian and western Semitic traditions in art, architecture, and religion.\n\nMari's greatest historical moment came in the early second millennium BC, when its palace archive yielded more than 25,000 clay tablets of diplomatic correspondence and administrative records — one of the richest archives of the ancient Near East. While these tablets post-date the era covered here, the city's significance as a commercial and political player was established during its early phase in the third millennium, laying the foundations for the later prominence that made Mari's archives so historically valuable.",
